  "texts": [
    "Specifically, we consider three training settings of LLMs, i.e., the zero-shot setting without fine-tuning, Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning (PEFT) setting (we use the LoRA [45] here) with a few parameters tuned, and Fine-Tuning (FT) setting with all parameters tuned, and summarize empirical conclusions from three aspects: overall performance of different settings, the impact of instruction tuning, and the impact of training data.• Overall performance of different settings.",
    "As shown in Table 5, we can see that the results of fine-tuning LLMs (PEFT and FT) on only 256 samples are significantly better than the zero-shot performance in cold-start scenarios, and empirical findings are consistent across four LLMs on both datasets.",
    "Furthermore, considering the two kinds of fine-tuning strategies, the performance of the fine-tuning setting is even better than that of the PEFT setting since more parameters are tuned [45].",
    "In addition to recommendation effects, training efficiency is also a performance that deserves attention.",
    "Therefore, we compare the training time of the two fine-tuning strategies on two datasets."
